{"id":"1704.04740","submitter":"Isabel Gonzalo Fonrodona","authors":"Miguel A. Porras, Isabel Gonzalo, and M. Ahmir Malik","title":"Lorenz curve of a light beam: evaluating beam quality from a\n  mayorization perspective","comments":"Errors corrected and Fig. 5 and some comments added","journal-ref":null,"doi":null,"report-no":null,"categories":"physics.optics","license":"http://arxiv.org/licenses/nonexclusive-distrib/1.0/","abstract":"  We introduce a novel approach for the characterization of the quality of a\nlaser beam that is not based on particular criteria for beam width definition.\nThe Lorenz curve of a light beam is a sophisticated version of the so-called\npower-in-the-bucket curve, formed by the partial sums of discretized joint\nintensity distribution in the near and far fields sorted in decreasing order.\nAccording to majorization theory, a higher Lorenz curve implies that all\nmeasures of spreading in phase space, and, in particular, all R\\'enyi (and\nShannon) entropy-based measures of the beam width products in near and far\nfields, are unanimously smaller, providing a strong assessment of a better beam\nquality. Two beams whose Lorenz curves intersect can only be considered of\nrelatively better or lower quality according to specific criteria, which can be\ninferred from the plot of the respective Lorenz curves.\n","versions":[{"version":"v1","created":"Sun, 16 Apr 2017 09:39:58 GMT"},{"version":"v2","created":"Fri, 28 Jul 2017 08:50:31 GMT"}],"update_date":"2017-07-31"}
